<dl id="n54103g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54103g">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54103g"> 103(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> caravan series <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54103g"><li>FW 285.21 </li><li><a href="../../flex/lg/lexlg.htm#n54103g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/lg/l39lg.htm#n54103g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54103g">MS BL 47478-342</ms> </li><li>JJA 53.321 <a name="lad13" href="../../ff/fdra/lda.htm#lgd14">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/lg/lgd14.htm#n54103g">Draft: II.2&sect;8.14</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The merchants travelled in companies or <mark>caravans</mark>, for the sake of safety, for there were many dangers to be faced before they could reach the end of their journey. A great part of the route lay through the desert, and here were often plunderers who might fall on the caravans, robbing them of all their treasures. A caravan may be large or small, a large one sometimes numbering over a thousand camels. <small> Edith Holland, <a name="EHSM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EHSM"><cite title="source">The Story of Mohammed</cite></a> (1914) 20-21</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
